Crimea and Sudetenland, same battle?
BRUSSELS – The annexation of Crimea by Russia constitutes the gravest example of aggression in peacetime that Europe has witnessed since the annexation of the Sudetenland by Nazi Germany in 1938.
It is certainly customary today to minimize the importance of the "lessons of Munich" when discussing this episode in which Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier capitulated to Hitler's demands on Czechoslovakia in order to pacify the Führer.
However, if the Western world were to turn a blind eye to the annexation of Crimea – the second case of an invasion of a sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, after the seizure of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 – current democratic leaders might well rue their inaction.
In Western capitals, reactions have so far been mixed.
The sanctions currently being considered – for example, expulsion from the G8 – might make one smile if the threat to European peace were not so serious.
Putin considers the collapse of the Soviet Union as the gravest catastrophe of modern times, the man striving without cease to revive a fallen Russian Empire.
If the West wants to be taken seriously, it will have to act with the same determination that Putin displays.
The numerous successes of the Russian president within his imperial project have cost him practically nothing so far.
His initiative for an Eurasian Economic Community has allowed Russia to rally a number of resource-rich states such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
The Georgian territory was divided in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidation forced it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here comes the most precious geostrategic trophy of all – Ukraine – that could very well fall into Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia ceases to be an empire, as explained by the former U.S. national security advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; 'however, with a suborned and subordinate Ukraine, Russia automatically becomes an empire again.' And since the vast majority of Ukrainians have no wish to join Putin's empire, it is highly likely that the country led by the Russian president is now an highly militarized state, akin to a Soviet Union without the Communist Party.
It is essential that the international community's reaction matches the degree of adventurism demonstrated by Putin.
cancellations of summits, proposals for trade agreements and other participation in forums as unproductive as the G8 can hardly suffice.
Only steps involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions, which could affect Russian citizens – who, let us remember, continue to re-elect Putin to power – will allow us to hope that the Kremlin will leave its expansionary trajectory.
What kind of sanctions could these be?
Firstly, Turkey could decide to close the Dardanelles strait to Russian transport, as it did after the Russo-Georgian war in 2008.
At the time, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea to prevent America from intervening, although it now appears clearly that this was not the intention of the United States.
Today, Turkey could choose not only to close the Turkish Straits to Russian warships but also to all commercial vessels sailing to Russian ports in the Black Sea.
The impact on the Russian economy – as well as on Putin's military ambitions – would be considerable.
Under an amendment made in 1982 to the 1936 Montreaux Convention, Turkey is authorized to close the Dardanelles.
Thus, Turkey could turn the justification used by Putin to annex Crimea against him – that he was protecting ethnic Russians living there – by asserting that it is itself protecting its Turks of Tatar descent, who, given the mistreatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule.
This week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to make an in-flight U-turn to head towards Kyiv to support the new interim government.
The first minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who as Putin knows is not a soft touch either, could thus follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish straits to Russian transport – until Putin withdraws his entire Crimean contingent so that they return to their bases, namely those in Sevastopol or Russia.
It would be good for Turkey to have the guarantee provided by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in case Russia attempts to intimidate it.
Secondly, US President Barack Obama could impose the same financial sanctions on Russia as he did on Iran regarding its nuclear program.
These sanctions have indeed seriously crippled the Iranian economy.
In the same way, refusing access to the American financial system to all banks dealing with Russian banks or companies would generate an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
Russians must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power was based on his promise to end the shortages of the early post-Soviet era – to continue his aggressive imperialist path could come at a great cost to them.
Thirdly, Obama could remind the Chinese of their role in the stability of Eurasia.
To Putin, the disintegration of the Soviet Union was the greatest geostrategic windfall one can imagine.
In an instant, this empire, which had taken millions of hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation, simply vanished into thin air.
Since then, the Central Asian states and Ukraine itself have become important commercial partners for China.
The invasion of Georgia by Russia seriously upset China, as could be seen at the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held after the war (this regional bloc bringing together a number of former Soviet states bordering both China and Mother Russia).
Russia tried to get the SCO to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
However, the organization expressed its disagreement.
Indeed, the Central Asian member countries – Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan – would never have been able to rise against the Kremlin without Chinese support.
It now falls to Chinese President Xi Jinping to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's bold moves.
The true test of China's claim to be a true and responsible protagonist within the international community will play out very soon at the United Nations.
Will China support this manifest violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it stand in support of Ukraine's territorial integrity?
Two other avenues for sanctions are also conceivable.
Each Russian leader could thus see their visas refused or canceled.
It would also be possible to freeze a number of assets, particularly those that have been laundered by Putin's close oligarchs.
This will only happen when the pain has become unbearable, particularly for the elites, at which point this kind of struggle that Putin is waging today will fail.
The cost of inaction could well turn out to be significant.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, rely on America's promise to act firmly against any serious threat to peace.
Moreover, when Ukraine renounced its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so under the explicit condition that the United States (alongside the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) would guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one can blame Ukraine if it decides to renuclearize its defense (which it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him with the famous formula: "You had the choice between war and dishonor.
You chose dishonor, and you will have war." Today, Obama and other Western leaders are faced with a similar choice.
If they were to choose dishonor, we can be certain that the bold Putin will sooner or later serve them another war.
